---
import CaseStudyLayout from "../layouts/CaseStudyLayout.astro";

const meta = [
  { label: "Year", value: "2021" },
  { label: "Client", value: "Porsche" },
  { label: "Role", value: "Lead Product Designer" },
  { label: "Agency", value: "Brandwidth" },
];

const stats = [
  { value: "watchOS", label: "Native build" },
  { value: "1", label: "Lead designer" },
  { value: "4", label: "Vital stats" },
  { value: "Live", label: "Telemetry" },
];
export const prerender = true;
---

<CaseStudyLayout
  pageTitle="Porsche — Sammy Norris"
  lede="Porsche on your wrist."
  meta={meta}
  description="A smartwatch app giving Porsche owners real-time access to their car's vital stats — designed from concept to handoff for Apple Watch."
  signoff="Designed at Brandwidth"
  signoffYear="2021"
>
  <Fragment slot="title">Porsche</Fragment>

  <!-- Figure 01 -->
  <figure class="figure" data-reveal>
    <picture>
      <source media="(max-width: 768px)" srcset="/images/projects/porsche/image-porsche-1-m.jpg" />
      <img src="/images/projects/porsche/image-porsche-1.jpg" alt="Porsche Apple Watch app hero" loading="eager" />
    </picture>
  </figure>

  <!-- Chapter I — Challenge -->
  <section class="chapter" data-reveal>
    <header class="chapter__head">
      <span class="chapter__num">I.</span>
      <span class="chapter__label b2">The challenge</span>
    </header>

    <blockquote class="chapter__quote">
      Porsche owners have a particular relationship with their cars. The
      brief was to deepen that connection — giving them instant, glanceable
      access to the information that mattered most, without picking up their
      phone.
    </blockquote>

    <div class="chapter__body">
      <p class="b1">
        The result was a native Apple Watch app that put charging status,
        mileage, fuel levels, and lock status directly on the wrist —
        translating Porsche's visual language to watchOS without losing its
        character or becoming generic utility software.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Figure 02 -->
  <figure class="figure" data-reveal>
    <picture>
      <source media="(max-width: 768px)" srcset="/images/projects/porsche/image-porsche-2-m.jpg" />
      <img src="/images/projects/porsche/image-porsche-2.jpg" alt="Apple Watch interface screens" loading="lazy" />
    </picture>
  </figure>

  <!-- Chapter II — Process -->
  <section class="chapter" data-reveal>
    <header class="chapter__head">
      <span class="chapter__num">II.</span>
      <span class="chapter__label b2">The process</span>
    </header>

    <h2 class="chapter__h2">
      Research first, <em>pixels second.</em>
    </h2>

    <div class="chapter__body chapter__body--double">
      <p class="b1">
        Working as part of the agency team at Brandwidth, I was the primary
        designer on the project, taking it from initial concept through to
        final handoff. The challenge wasn't just designing for a small screen
        — it was designing for a brand with exceptionally high standards,
        where every detail needed to feel considered and premium.
      </p>
      <p class="b1">
        The design process was grounded in research from the start. We spoke
        with Porsche owners to understand how and when they actually wanted
        to interact with their car's data — what was genuinely useful at a
        glance versus what belonged in a deeper interface. That insight
        shaped the information hierarchy and interaction model throughout.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Figure 03 -->
  <figure class="figure" data-reveal>
    <picture>
      <source media="(max-width: 768px)" srcset="/images/projects/porsche/image-porsche-3-m.jpg" />
      <img src="/images/projects/porsche/image-porsche-3.jpg" alt="Live telemetry on watchOS" loading="lazy" />
    </picture>
  </figure>

  <!-- Chapter III — Outcome -->
  <section class="chapter" data-reveal>
    <header class="chapter__head">
      <span class="chapter__num">III.</span>
      <span class="chapter__label b2">The outcome</span>
    </header>

    <h2 class="chapter__h2">
      Now part of <em>Porsche Connect.</em>
    </h2>

    <div class="stats">
      {stats.map((s) => (
        <div class="stat">
          <span class="stat__value">{s.value}</span>
          <span class="stat__label b3">{s.label}</span>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>

    <div class="chapter__body">
      <p class="b1">
        Telemetry communication was at the core of the product — real-time
        data pulled directly from the vehicle and surfaced cleanly on the
        watch face. Designing around live data meant accounting for edge
        cases, connectivity states, and moments where information simply
        wasn't available, all while keeping the experience feeling seamless.
        The app shipped as part of what is now known as Porsche Connect.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Figure 04 -->
  <figure class="figure" data-reveal>
    <picture>
      <source media="(max-width: 768px)" srcset="/images/projects/porsche/image-porsche-4-m.jpg" />
      <img src="/images/projects/porsche/image-porsche-4.jpg" alt="Watch face detail" loading="lazy" />
    </picture>
  </figure>

  <!-- Figure 05 -->
  <figure class="figure" data-reveal>
    <picture>
      <source media="(max-width: 768px)" srcset="/images/projects/porsche/image-porsche-5-m.jpg" />
      <img src="/images/projects/porsche/image-porsche-5.jpg" alt="Porsche Connect on Apple Watch" loading="lazy" />
    </picture>
  </figure>

  <!-- Figure 06 -->
  <figure class="figure" data-reveal>
    <picture>
      <source media="(max-width: 768px)" srcset="/images/projects/porsche/image-porsche-6-m.jpg" />
      <img src="/images/projects/porsche/image-porsche-6.jpg" alt="Porsche Apple Watch detail" loading="lazy" />
    </picture>
  </figure>
</CaseStudyLayout>
